===Etymology 1===
{{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|riht|lang=ang}}, from Germanic ''*rekhtaz'', from Indo-European ''*reg-to-'' ‘having moved in a straight line’. An Indo-European past participle, it became a Germanic adjective which has been used also as a noun since the common Germanic period. Cognate with Dutch [[recht#Dutch|recht]], German [[recht]]/[[Recht]], Swedish [[rätt]], and Norwegian [[rett]]. The Indo-European root is also the source of Greek [[ὀρεκτός]], Latin [[rectus]] and the [[Sanskrit]] [[ṛtá]] (ऋत)

